# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: interactive-visualization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:interactive-visualization/brushing-and-linking] In databases, **brushing and linking** is the connection of two or more views of the same data, such that a change to the representation in one view affects the representation in the other.
[src:interactive-visualization/brushing-and-linking] Brushing and linking is also an important technique in interactive visual analysis, a method for performing visual exploration and analysis of large, structured data sets.
[src:interactive-visualization/brushing-and-linking] Specifically, linking consists of a change of parameters (for example a data filter) in one data representation being reflected in other connected data representations.
[src:interactive-visualization/brushing-and-linking] Brushing may, for example, highlight the selected data from one view in other connected data representations.
[src:interactive-visualization/brushing-and-linking] One example might be a two-part display, consisting of a histogram alongside a list of document titles.
[src:interactive-visualization/brushing-and-linking] The histogram could show how many documents were published each month.
[src:interactive-visualization/brushing-and-linking] Brushing and linking would allow the user to assign a color, green for instance, to one bar of the histogram, thus causing the titles in the list display that were published during the corresponding month to also be highlighted in green.
[src:interactive-visualization/brushing-and-linking] The technique and name 'brushing' were introduced in the 1980s by Richard A.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:interactive-visualization/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] A **fisheye lens** is an ultra wide-angle lens that produces strong visual distortion intended to create a wide panoramic or hemispherical image.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Fisheye lenses achieve extremely wide angles of view, well beyond any rectilinear lens.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Instead of producing images with straight lines of perspective (rectilinear images), fisheye lenses use a special mapping ("distortion"; for example: equisolid angle, see below), which gives images a characteristic convex non-rectilinear appearance.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The term *fisheye* was coined in 1906 by American physicist and inventor Robert W.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Wood based on how a fish would see an ultrawide hemispherical view from beneath the water (a phenomenon known as Snell's window).
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Their first practical use was in the 1920s for use in meteorology to study cloud formation giving them the name *whole-sky lenses*.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The angle of view of a fisheye lens is usually between 100 and 180 degrees, although lenses covering up to 280 degrees exist (see below).
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Their focal lengths depend on the film format they are designed for.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Mass-produced fisheye lenses for photography first appeared in the early 1960s and are generally used for their unique, distorted appearance.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] For the popular 35 mm film format, typical focal lengths of fisheye lenses are 8–10 mm for circular images, and 12–18 mm for diagonal images filling the entire frame.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] For digital cameras using smaller imagers such as 1/4 in and 1/3 in format CCD or CMOS sensors, the focal length of "miniature" fisheye lenses can be as short as 1–2 mm.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Fisheye lenses also have other applications, such as re-projecting images originally filmed through a fisheye lens, or created via computer-generated graphics, onto hemispherical screens.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] They are also used for scientific photography, such as recordings of aurora and meteors, and to study plant canopy geometry, and to calculate near-ground solar radiation.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] In everyday life, they are perhaps most commonly encountered as peephole door viewers to give a wide field of view.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Panoramas with fisheye distortion predate photography and the fisheye lens.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] In 1779, Horace Bénédict de Saussure published his downward-facing fisheye view of the Alps: "All the objects are drawn in perspective from the centre".
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The experiment was Wood's attempt "to ascertain how the external world appears to the fish" and hence the title of the paper was "Fish-Eye Views, and Vision under Water".
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Wood subsequently built an improved "horizontal" version of the camera omitting the lens, instead using a pinhole pierced in the side of a tank, which was filled with water and a photographic plate.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] In the text, he described a third "Fish-Eye" camera built using sheet brass, the primary advantages being that this one was more portable than the other two cameras, and was "absolutely leaktight".
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Bond described an improvement to Wood's apparatus in 1922 which replaced the tank of water with a simple hemispheric glass lens, making the camera significantly more portable.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The focal length depended on the refractive index and radius of the hemispherical lens, and the maximum aperture was approximately f/50; it was not corrected for chromatic aberration and projected a curved field onto a flat plate.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Bond noted the new lens could be used to record cloud cover or lightning strikes at a given location.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Bond's hemispheric lens also reduced the need for a pinhole aperture to ensure sharp focus, so exposure times were also reduced.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] In 1924, Robin Hill first described a lens with 180° coverage that had been used for a cloud survey in September 1923 The lens, designed by Hill and R. & J.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Beck, Ltd., was patented in December 1923.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The Hill *Sky Lens* is now credited as the first fisheye lens.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Hill also described three different mapping functions of a lens designed to capture an entire hemisphere (stereographic, equidistant, and orthographic).
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Distortion is unavoidable in a lens that encompasses an angle of view exceeding 125°, but Hill and Beck claimed in the patent that stereographic or equidistant projection were the preferred mapping functions.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The three-element, three-group lens design uses a highly divergent meniscus lens as the first element to bring in light over a wide view followed by a converging lens system to project the view onto a flat photographic plate.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The Hill *Sky Lens* was fitted to a whole sky camera, typically used in a pair separated by 500 metres (1,600 ft) for stereo imaging, and equipped with a red filter for contrast; in its original form, the lens had a focal length of 0.84 in (21 mm) and cast an image 2.5 in (64 mm) in diameter at f/8.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Conrad Beck described the camera system in an article published in 1925.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] In 1932, the German firm Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft AG (AEG) filed for a patent on the *Weitwinkelobjektiv* (wide-angle lens), a 5-element, 4-group development of the Hill *Sky Lens*.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Compared to the 1923 Hill *Sky Lens*, the 1932 *Weitwinkelobjektiv* featured two diverging meniscus elements ahead of the stop and used a cemented achromatic group in the converging section.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Miyamoto credits Hans Schulz with the design of the *Weitwinkelobjektiv*.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The basic patented design was produced for cloud recording as a 17 mm f/6.3 lens, and Umbo used the AEG lens for artistic purposes, with photographs published in a 1937 issue of *Volk und Welt*.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The AEG *Weitwinkelobjektiv* formed the basis of the later Nippon Kogaku (Nikon) *Fisheye-Nikkor* 16 mm f/8 lens of 1938, which was used for military and scientific (cloud cover) purposes.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Nikon, which had a contract to supply optics to the Imperial Japanese Navy, possibly gained access to the AEG design under the Pact of Steel.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Also in 1938, Robert Richter of Carl Zeiss AG patented the 6-element, 5-group *Pleon* lens, which was used for aerial surveillance during World War II.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The converging rear group of the Pleon was symmetrical, derived from the 4-element *Topogon* lens designed by Richter for Zeiss in 1933.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Testing on a captured lens after the war showed the *Pleon* provided an equidistant projection to cover a field of approximately 130°, and negatives were printed using a special rectifying enlarger to eliminate distortion.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The *Pleon* had a focal length of approximately 72.5 mm with a maximum aperture of f/8 and used a plano-concave front element 300 mm (12 in) in diameter; the image on the negative was approximately 85 mm (3.3 in) in diameter.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] At approximately the same time that Schulz was developing the *Weitwinkelobjektiv* at AEG, Willy Merté at Zeiss was developing the *Sphaerogon*, which was also designed to encompass a 180° field of view.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Unlike the *Weitwinkelobjektiv*, Merté's *Sphaerogon* was not limited to medium format cameras; prototype versions of the *Sphaerogon* were constructed for the Contax I miniature format camera.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The first prototype *Sphaerogon* lenses constructed had a maximum aperture of f/8, but later examples were computed half a stop faster, to f/6.8.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The revised lens created a circular image 50 mm (2.0 in) in diameter and covered a complete hemispherical field of 180°.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Only 30 examples of the Nikon Fisheye Camera were manufactured, and of those, 18 were sold to customers, mainly in the United States; Nikon likely destroyed the remaining stock to avoid tax penalties.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Prior to the early 1960s, fisheye lenses were used primarily by professional and scientific photographers, but the advent of the fisheye for the 35 mm format increased its popular use.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The *Fisheye-Nikkor* 8 mm f/8 has a field of view of 180° and uses 9 elements in 5 groups; it has a fixed focus and built-in filters intended for black-and-white photography.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Research indicates that fewer than 1,400 lenses were built.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] As fisheye lenses became more widely available, the distinctive distortion grew in popularity, especially for album covers.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] For example, British fashion photographer Tim Walker used a fisheye lens to capture the cover of Harry Styles' 2019 pop/rock album, *Fine Line*.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Other genres that have taken advantage of the fisheye lens look include punk rock, hip-hop, and skateboarding videos.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] In particular, the fisheye lens became a signature style of music video director Hype Williams, especially in the mid-to-late 1990s when he directed videos for artists such as Busta Rhymes, Missy Elliott, and Puff Daddy.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Contemporaneously, other Japanese manufacturers were developing the so-called "full-frame" or diagonal fisheyes, which captured approximately a 180° field of view across the diagonal of the film frame.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The first such diagonal fisheye was the *Fish-eye Takumar* 18 mm f/11, released by Pentax (Asahi Optical) in 1962, followed by the slightly faster *UW Rokkor-PG* 18 mm f/9.5 from Minolta in 1966.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Both of these were reflex-viewing and fixed-focus.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Both Pentax and Minolta followed up with faster lenses with variable focus in 1967 (*Super Fish-eye-Takumar* 17 mm f/4) and 1969 (*Rokkor-OK* 16 mm f/2.8), respectively.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The 16 mm Rokkor was later adopted by Leica as the *Fisheye-Elmarit-R* (1974) for its SLRs and then converted to autofocus (1986) for the Alpha system.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] As of 2018, the same basic optical design is still sold as the Sony SAL16F28.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Unlike rectilinear lenses, fisheye lenses are not fully characterised by focal length and aperture alone.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Angle of view, image diameter, projection type, and sensor coverage all vary independently of these.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] In a **circular fisheye lens**, the image circle is *inscribed in* the film or sensor area; in a **diagonal ("full-frame") fisheye lens**, the image circle is *circumscribed around* the film or sensor area.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] This implies that using a fisheye lens for a different format than it was intended for is easy (as opposed to a rectilinear lens), and may change its characteristic.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Although there are digital fisheye effects available both in-camera and as computer software, neither can extend the angle of view of the original images to the very large one of a true fisheye lens.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The focal length is determined by the angular coverage, the specific mapping function used, and the required dimensions of the final image.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] For circular fisheyes, the maximum dimension r is half the length of the shortest side.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] For full-frame fisheyes, the maximum dimension r is half the length of the diagonal.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The first types of fisheye lenses developed were "circular" — lenses which took in a 180° hemisphere and projected it as a circle within the film frame.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] By design, circular fisheye lenses thus cover a smaller image circle than rectilinear lenses designed for the same sensor size.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The corners of a circular fisheye image will be completely black.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] This blackness is different from the gradual vignetting of rectilinear lenses and sets on abruptly.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Some circular fisheyes were available in orthographic projection models for scientific applications.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] These have a 180° *vertical,* horizontal and diagonal angle of view.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] For APS and m43 cameras, several lenses have emerged that retain a 180° field of view on a crop body.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The first of these was the Sigma 4.5 mm.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Sunex also makes a 5.6 mm fisheye lens that captures a circular 185° field of view on a 1.5x Nikon and 1.6x Canon DSLR cameras.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Nikon produced a 6 mm circular fisheye lens for 35 mm film that was initially designed for an expedition to Antarctica.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] It featured a 220° field of view, designed to capture the entire sky and surrounding ground when pointed straight up.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] This lens is no longer manufactured, and is used nowadays to produce interactive virtual-reality images such as QuickTime VR and IPIX.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Because of its very wide field of view, it is very large — weighing 5.2 kilograms (11 lb), having a diameter of 236 millimetres (9.3 in), a length of 171 millimetres (6.7 in) and an angle of view of 220 degrees.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] It dwarfs a regular 35 mm SLR camera and has its own tripod mounting point, a feature normally seen in large long-focus or telephoto lenses to reduce strain on the lens mount.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] More recently, the Japanese manufacturer Entaniya offers several fisheye lenses with angles of view up to 250° on 35 mm full frame, and up to 280° on smaller sensors (see list below), intended for use in virtual reality applications.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] In 2018, Venus Optics introduced a 210° fisheye lens for the Micro Four Thirds system.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The 8 mm and 7.5 mm circular fisheye lenses made by Nikon have proven useful for scientific purposes because of their equidistant (equiangular) projection, in which distance along the radius of the circular image is proportional to the zenith angle.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] As fisheye lenses gained popularity in general photography, camera companies began manufacturing fisheye lenses with an enlarged image circle to cover the entire rectangular film frame.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] They are called diagonal, or sometimes "rectangular" or "full-frame", fisheyes.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] (This was well before digital photography, so the use of the term "full frame" with respect to fisheyes has nothing to do with the use of the term to designate a digital sensor measuring 36x24 mm).
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The angle of view produced by diagonal fisheyes only measures 180° *from corner to corner*: they have a 180° *diagonal* angle of view (AOV), while the horizontal and vertical angles of view will be smaller.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] For an equisolid angle 15 mm full-frame fisheye, the horizontal AOV will be 147°, and the vertical AOV will be 94°.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] One of the first diagonal fisheye lenses to be mass-produced was the Nikon Fisheye-Nikkor F 16mm f/3.5, made in the early 1970s.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] To obtain the same effect on digital cameras with smaller sensors, shorter focal lengths are required.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Nikon makes a 10.5 mm fisheye for their APS DX SLRs.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Several other companies make "full frame", i.e. diagonal, fisheyes for APS and m43 cameras, see next paragraph.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] An intermediate between a diagonal and a circular fisheye consists of a circular image optimised for the *width* of the film format rather than the *height*.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] As a result, on any non-square film format, the circular image will be cropped at the top and bottom, but still show black edges on the left and right.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] This format is called a "portrait" fisheye; historically, it has been rather rare – only the 12 mm f/8 Accura lens (see list below) directly follows the portrait principle.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Today however, a portrait fisheye effect is easily achieved by using a fisheye lens intended for full coverage of a smaller sensor format, like an APS diagonal fisheye on a 35 mm full frame camera, or an m43 diagonal fisheye on APS.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Miniature digital cameras, especially when used as security cameras, often tend to have fisheye lenses to maximize coverage.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Miniature fisheye lenses are designed for small-format CCD/CMOS imagers commonly used in consumer and security cameras.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Popular image sensor format sizes used include 1⁄4", 1⁄3", and 1⁄2".
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Depending on the active area of the image sensor, the same lens can form a circular image on a larger image sensor (e.g.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] 1⁄2"), and a full frame on a smaller one (e.g.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] For a comprehensive list of all current and all past fisheye lenses, see External Links below.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The APS-C image sensor used in Canon cameras is 22.3 mm × 14.9 mm, or 26.82 mm on the diagonal, which is slightly smaller than the sensor size used by other popular manufacturers of cameras with APS-C sensors, such as Fuji, Minolta, Nikon, Pentax, and Sony.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The other common APS-C sensors are 23.6–23.7 mm on the long dimension and 15.6 mm on the shorter side, for a diagonal dimension of 28.2–28.4 mm.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The subject is placed in the image by the lens according to the *mapping function* of the lens.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] The mapping function gives r, the position of the object from the center of the image, as a function of f, the focal length, and θ, the angle from the optical axis, in radians.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Other mapping functions (for example Panomorph Lenses) are also possible for enhancing the off-axis resolution of fisheye lenses.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] With appropriate software, the curvilinear images produced by a fisheye lens can be remapped to a conventional rectilinear projection.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Although this entails some loss of detail at the edges of the frame, the technique can produce an image with a field of view greater than that of a conventional rectilinear lens.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] This is particularly useful for creating panoramic images.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] All types of fisheye lenses bend straight lines.
[src:interactive-visualization/fisheye-lens] Aperture angles of 180° or more are possible only with large amounts of barrel distortion.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] An **interaction technique**, **user interface technique** or **input technique** is a combination of hardware and software elements that provides a way for computer users to accomplish a single task.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] For example, one can go back to the previously visited page on a Web browser by either clicking a button, pressing a key, performing a mouse gesture or uttering a speech command.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] It is a widely used term in human-computer interaction.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] In particular, the term "new interaction technique" is frequently used to introduce a novel user interface design idea.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Consider for example the process of deleting a file using a contextual menu.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] This assumes the existence of a mouse (input device), a screen (output device), and a piece of code that paints a menu and updates its selection (user feedback) and sends a command to the file system when the user clicks on the "delete" item (interpretation).
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] User feedback can be further used to confirm that the command has been invoked.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] From the user's perspective, an interaction technique is a way to perform a single computing task and can be informally expressed with user instructions or usage scenarios.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] For example, "to delete a file, right-click on the file you want to delete, then click on the delete item".
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] From the user interface designer's perspective, an interaction technique is a well-defined solution to a specific user interface design problem.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Interaction techniques as conceptual ideas can be refined, extended, modified and combined.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] For example, contextual menus are a solution to the problem of rapidly selecting commands.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Pie menus are a radial variant of contextual menus.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Marking menus combine pie menus with gesture recognition.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] One extant cause of confusion in the general discussion of interaction is a lack of clarity about levels of granularity.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Interaction techniques are usually characterized at a low level of granularity—not necessarily at the lowest level of physical events, but at a level that is technology-, platform-, and implementation-dependent.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] For example, interaction techniques exist that are specific to mobile devices, touch-based displays, traditional mouse/keyboard inputs, and other paradigms—in other words, they are dependent on a specific technology or platform.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] In contrast, viewed at higher levels of granularity, interaction is not tied to any specific technology or platform.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] The interaction of 'filtering', for example, can be characterized in a way that is technology-independent—e.g., performing an action such that some information is hidden and only a subset of the original information remains.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Such an interaction could be implemented using any number of techniques, and on any number of platforms and technologies.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] See also the discussion of interaction patterns below.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] An interaction task is "the unit of an entry of information by the user", such as entering a piece of text, issuing a command, or specifying a 2D position.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] A similar concept is that of domain object, which is a piece of application data that can be manipulated by the user.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Interaction techniques are the glue between physical I/O devices and interaction tasks or domain objects.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Different types of interaction techniques can be used to map a specific device to a specific domain object.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] For example, different gesture alphabets exist for pen-based text input.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] In general, the less compatible the device is with the domain object, the more complex the interaction technique.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] For example, using a mouse to specify a 2D point involves a trivial interaction technique, whereas using a mouse to rotate a 3D object requires more creativity to design the technique and more lines of code to implement it.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] A current trend is to avoid complex interaction techniques by matching physical devices with the task as close as possible, such as exemplified by the field of tangible computing.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] But this is not always a feasible solution.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Furthermore, device/task incompatibilities are unavoidable in computer accessibility, where a single switch can be used to control the whole computer environment.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Interaction techniques that share the same metaphor or design principles can be seen as belonging to the same interaction style.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] General examples are command line and direct manipulation user interfaces.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] While interaction techniques are typically technology-, platform-, and implementation-dependent (see § Level of granularity above), human-computer or human-information interactions can be characterized at higher levels of abstraction that are independent of particular technologies and platforms.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] At such levels of abstraction, the concern is not precisely how an interaction is performed; rather, the concern is a conceptual characterization of what the interaction is, and what the general utility of the interaction is for the user(s).
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Thus, any single interaction pattern may be instantiated by any number of interaction techniques, on any number of different technologies and platforms.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Interaction patterns are more concerned with the timeless, invariant qualities of an interaction.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Interaction techniques essentially involve data entry and manipulation, and thus place greater emphasis on input than output.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Output is merely used to convey affordances and provide user feedback.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] The use of the term *input technique* further reinforces the central role of input.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Conversely, techniques that mainly involve data exploration and thus place greater emphasis on output are called visualization techniques.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] They are studied in the field of information visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] A large part of research in human-computer interaction involves exploring easier-to-learn or more efficient interaction techniques for common computing tasks.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] This includes inventing new (post-WIMP) interaction techniques, possibly relying on methods from user interface design, and assessing their efficiency with respect to existing techniques using methods from experimental psychology.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Examples of scientific venues in these topics are the UIST and the CHI conferences.
[src:interactive-visualization/interaction-technique] Other research focuses on the specification of interaction techniques, sometimes using formalisms such as Petri nets for the purposes of formal verification.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Visualization today has ever-expanding applications in science, education, engineering (e.g., product visualization), interactive multimedia, medicine, etc.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Typical of a visualization application is the field of computer graphics.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The invention of computer graphics (and 3D computer graphics) may be the most important development in visualization since the invention of central perspective in the Renaissance period.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The development of animation also helped advance visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The use of visualization to present information is not a new phenomenon.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] It has been used in maps, scientific drawings, and data plots for over a thousand years.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Examples from cartography include Ptolemy's Geographia (2nd century AD), a map of China (1137 AD), and Minard's map (1861) of Napoleon's invasion of Russia a century and a half ago.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Most of the concepts learned in devising these images carry over in a straightforward manner to computer visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Edward Tufte has written three critically acclaimed books that explain many of these principles.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Computer graphics has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the publication of Visualization in Scientific Computing, a special issue of Computer Graphics.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Since then, there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH, devoted to the general topic, and special areas in the field, for example volume visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Most people are familiar with the digital animations produced to present meteorological data during weather reports on television, though few can distinguish between those models of reality and the satellite photos that are also shown on such programs.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] TV also offers scientific visualizations when it shows computer drawn and animated reconstructions of road or airplane accidents.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Some of the most popular examples of scientific visualizations are computer-generated images that show real spacecraft in action, out in the void far beyond Earth, or on other planets.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Dynamic forms of visualization, such as educational animation or timelines, have the potential to enhance learning about systems that change over time.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Apart from the distinction between interactive visualizations and animation, the most useful categorization is probably between abstract and model-based scientific visualizations.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The abstract visualizations show completely conceptual constructs in 2D or 3D.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] These generated shapes are completely arbitrary.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The model-based visualizations either place overlays of data on real or digitally constructed images of reality or make a digital construction of a real object directly from the scientific data.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is usually done with specialized software, though there are a few exceptions, noted below.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Some of these specialized programs have been released as open source software, having very often its origins in universities, within an academic environment where sharing software tools and giving access to the source code is common.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] There are also many proprietary software packages of scientific visualization tools.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Models and frameworks for building visualizations include the data flow models popularized by systems such as AVS, IRIS Explorer, and VTK toolkit, and data state models in spreadsheet systems such as the Spreadsheet for Visualization and Spreadsheet for Images.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] As a subject in computer science, scientific visualization is the use of interactive, sensory representations, typically visual, of abstract data to reinforce cognition, hypothesis building, and reasoning.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is the transformation, selection, or representation of data from simulations or experiments, with an implicit or explicit geometric structure, to allow the exploration, analysis, and understanding of the data.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization focuses and emphasizes the representation of higher order data using primarily graphics and animation techniques.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] It is a very important part of visualization and maybe the first one, as the visualization of experiments and phenomena is as old as science itself.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Traditional areas of scientific visualization are flow visualization, medical visualization, astrophysical visualization, and chemical visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] There are several different techniques to visualize scientific data, with isosurface reconstruction and direct volume rendering being the more common.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Data visualization is a related subcategory of visualization dealing with statistical graphics and geospatial data (as in thematic cartography) that is abstracted in schematic form.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to explore large amount of abstract data.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The term "information visualization" was originally coined by the User Interface Research Group at Xerox PARC and included Jock Mackinlay.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Practical application of information visualization in computer programs involves selecting, transforming, and representing abstract data in a form that facilitates human interaction for exploration and understanding.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Important aspects of information visualization are dynamics of visual representation and the interactivity.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Strong techniques enable the user to modify the visualization in real-time, thus affording unparalleled perception of patterns and structural relations in the abstract data in question.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Educational visualization is using a simulation to create an image of something so it can be taught about.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] This is very useful when teaching about a topic that is difficult to otherwise see, for example, atomic structure, because atoms are far too small to be studied easily without expensive and difficult to use scientific equipment.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The use of visual representations to transfer knowledge between at least two persons aims to improve the transfer of knowledge by using computer and non-computer-based visualization methods complementarily.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Thus properly designed visualization is an important part of not only data analysis but knowledge transfer process, too.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Knowledge transfer may be significantly improved using hybrid designs as it enhances information density but may decrease clarity as well.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] For example, visualization of a 3D scalar field may be implemented using iso-surfaces for field distribution and textures for the gradient of the field.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Examples of such visual formats are sketches, diagrams, images, objects, interactive visualizations, information visualization applications, and imaginary visualizations as in stories.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] While information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to derive new insights, knowledge visualization focuses on transferring insights and creating new knowledge in groups.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Beyond the mere transfer of facts, knowledge visualization aims to further transfer insights, experiences, attitudes, values, expectations, perspectives, opinions, and estimates in different fields by using various complementary visualizations.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Product visualization involves visualization software technology for the viewing and manipulation of 3D models, technical drawing and other related documentation of manufactured components and large assemblies of products.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] It is a key part of product lifecycle management.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Product visualization software typically provides high levels of photorealism so that a product can be viewed before it is actually manufactured.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] This supports functions ranging from design and styling to sales and marketing.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] *Technical visualization* is an important aspect of product development.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Originally technical drawings were made by hand, but with the rise of advanced computer graphics the drawing board has been replaced by computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] CAD-drawings and models have several advantages over hand-made drawings such as the possibility of 3-D modeling, rapid prototyping, and simulation.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] 3D product visualization promises more interactive experiences for online shoppers, but also challenges retailers to overcome hurdles in the production of 3D content, as large-scale 3D content production can be extremely costly and time-consuming.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] In recent years, product visualization has increasingly incorporated interactive and real-time technologies, particularly in e-commerce environments.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Modern 3D visualization tools enable users to explore products in detail, customize attributes such as color, materials, and configuration, and view items in simulated or real-world contexts.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] These capabilities enhance user engagement and support more informed decision-making by providing realistic and context-aware representations of products.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] As a result, product visualization can help reduce uncertainty prior to purchase and contribute to lower product return rates.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Visual communication is the communication of ideas through the visual display of information.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Primarily associated with two dimensional images, it includes: alphanumerics, art, signs, and electronic resources.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Recent research in the field has focused on web design and graphically oriented usability.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics focuses on human interaction with visualization systems as part of a larger process of data analysis.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics has been defined as "the science of analytical reasoning supported by the interactive visual interface".
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Its focus is on human information discourse (interaction) within massive, dynamically changing information spaces.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics research concentrates on support for perceptual and cognitive operations that enable users to detect the expected and discover the unexpected in complex information spaces.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Technologies resulting from visual analytics find their application in almost all fields, but are being driven by critical needs (and funding) in biology and national security.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] One particular type of interactive visualization is virtual reality (VR), where the visual representation of information is presented using an immersive display device such as a stereo projector (see stereoscopy).
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Another type of interactive visualization is collaborative visualization, in which multiple people interact with the same computer visualization to communicate their ideas to each other or to explore information cooperatively.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Frequently, collaborative visualization is used when people are physically separated.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Using several networked computers, the same visualization can be presented to each person simultaneously.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The people then make annotations to the visualization as well as communicate via audio (i.e., telephone), video (i.e., a video-conference), or text (i.e., IRC) messages.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The Programmer's Hierarchical Interactive Graphics System (PHIGS) was one of the first programmatic efforts at interactive visualization and provided an enumeration of the types of input humans provide.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] All of these actions require a physical device.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Input devices range from the common – keyboards, mice, graphics tablets, trackballs, and touchpads – to the esoteric – wired gloves, boom arms, and even omnidirectional treadmills.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] These input actions can be used to control both the unique information being represented or the way that the information is presented.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] When the information being presented is altered, the visualization is usually part of a feedback loop.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] For example, consider an aircraft avionics system where the pilot inputs roll, pitch, and yaw and the visualization system provides a rendering of the aircraft's new attitude.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Another example would be a scientist who changes a simulation while it is running in response to a visualization of its current progress.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] This is called *computational steering*.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] More frequently, the representation of the information is changed rather than the information itself.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Experiments have shown that a delay of more than 20 ms between when input is provided and a visual representation is updated is noticeable by most people .
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Thus it is desirable for an interactive visualization to provide a rendering based on human input within this time frame.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] However, when large amounts of data must be processed to create a visualization, this becomes hard or even impossible with current technology.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Thus the term "interactive visualization" is usually applied to systems that provide feedback to users within several seconds of input.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The term *interactive framerate* is often used to measure how interactive a visualization is.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Framerates measure the frequency with which an image (a frame) can be generated by a visualization system.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] A framerate of 50 frames per second (frame/s) is considered good while 0.1 frame/s would be considered poor.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The use of framerates to characterize interactivity is slightly misleading however, since framerate is a measure of bandwidth while humans are more sensitive to latency.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Specifically, it is possible to achieve a good framerate of 50 frame/s but if the images generated refer to changes to the visualization that a person made more than 1 second ago, it will not feel interactive to a person.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] The rapid response time required for interactive visualization is a difficult constraint to meet and there are several approaches that have been explored to provide people with rapid visual feedback based on their input.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] *Progressive rendering* – where a framerate is guaranteed by rendering some subset of the information to be presented and providing incremental (progressive) improvements to the rendering once the visualization is no longer changing.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] *Level-of-detail (LOD) rendering* – where simplified representations of information are rendered to achieve a desired framerate while a person is providing input and then the full representation is used to generate a still image once the person is through manipulating the visualization.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] Subsampling can also be used to accelerate rendering techniques such as volume visualization that require more than twice the computations for an image twice the size.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] By rendering a smaller image and then scaling the image to fill the requested screen space, much less time is required to render the same data.
[src:interactive-visualization/interactive-visualization] *Frameless rendering* – where the visualization is no longer presented as a time series of images, but as a single image where different regions are updated over time.
